xhr.ontimeout = function (e) {
// Request timed out
};
xhr.send(null);
The fetch web API is a modern replacement for XMLHttp Request
that uses Promises. When the fetch API was initially introduced,
there was no way to set a timeout at all. Browsers have only later
added support for timeouts through the Abort API. Things aren’t
much rosier for Python; the popular requests library uses a default
timeout of infinity. And Go’s HTTP package doesn’t use timeouts
by default.
Modern HTTP clients for Java andNET do a better job and usually,
come with default timeouts. For example,.NET Core Http Client
has a default timeout of 100 seconds. It’s lax but arguably better
than not having a timeout at all.
As a rule of thumb, always set timeouts when making network
calls, and be wary of third-party libraries that make network calls
